vi and Vim Editors Pocket Reference

Introduction

This pocket reference is a companion to Learning the vi and Vim Editors, by Arnold Robbins et al.It describes the vi com-mand-line options, command-mode commands, ex com-mands and options, regular espressions and the use of the substitute (s) command, and other pertinent information for using vi.

While retaining coverage of the vi clones, nvi elvis, and vile, this edition offers espanded coverage of the Vim editor,
which has become thd de facto standard version of vi in the GNU/Linux world.

The Solaris version of served as the "reference" version fo the original vi for this pocker reference.

Conventions

The following font conventions are used in this book:
Courier
Used for filenames, command names, options, and every-thing to be typed literally.

Courier Italic

Uesd for replacceable text within commands.
Italic

Uesd for replaccable text within regular text, Internet
URLs, for emphasis, and for new terms when first defined.
[...]
Identifies optional text; the brackets are not typed.
CTRL-G
Indicates a keystroke.

